{% block content %}
  <h2>What the settlement covers</h2>
  <p>This settlement is for past compensation, the annuities that should have been paid and were not. The separate question of the go-forward annuity, what the yearly payment should be from here on, is still being negotiated between the nations and the Crown and is not yet set. For the fuller picture of all the moving parts, see <a href="/treaty">what the treaty is and what is happening now</a>.</p>

  <h2>How it is being shared</h2>
  <p>Each nation decides how its share is held and distributed, so the details differ community by community. The treaty-wide and community transparency questions on this site (in the <a href="/standard">Transparency</a> section) are the plain questions any member can ask their own council about how their nation's share is governed. For the per-capita versus collective question laid out neutrally, see <a href="/treaty/distribution-models">distribution models</a>.</p>

  <h2>Questions members are asking</h2>
  <p>These are common, fair questions. Where the public record gives an answer, we point to it; where it does not, we say so.</p>

  <h3>The legal fees</h3>
  <p>The fees charged to the litigation were challenged in court, and a judge ordered them reduced substantially, by reporting around $487 million. The disbursement and fee records are part of what members can ask the litigation fund to share.</p>

  <h3>The off-list and general-list members</h3>
  <p>Members who are not on a community's list, sometimes called the general list or the Sudbury 817, have reported still waiting on their share. This remains a live concern and is worth asking about directly.</p>

  <h3>Income assistance</h3>
  <p>A settlement payment can interact with income support like Ontario Works and ODSP. Before spending or banking a large payment, it is worth getting advice on how it may affect eligibility. The Income Security Advocacy Centre and Indigenous legal services can help. We do not give legal or financial advice; confirm your own situation with someone qualified.</p>

